[I have combined a number of disparate messages in one. At most, it can be
said that they are all related to the mixed Japanese encephalitis
virus/Hendra-like virus epizoodemic in Malaysia. I trust our subscribers
will read them as such and not draw any conclusions as to relationships
between them. - Mod.CHC
[1
THAI RESPONSE
Date: Tue, 23 Mar 1999 20:14:04 -0500
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source:  Xinhua News Agency, 22 Mar 1999 23:04

Thai officials claimed that the country's southern provinces, bordering
Malaysia, are free of the deadly Japanese encephalitis virus, the Bangkok
Post reported Tuesday. The newspaper quoted Suwithaya Pollarp, Livestock
Department director-general, as saying that no report was received so far
about human or animal ailments resulting from Japanese encephalitis [virus
infection. But he also said that the country has beefed up its security
inspections at border provinces in the south to prevent an outbreak of the
disease, which has claimed at least 53 lives in neighboring Malaysia.
The outbreak of the disease has resulted in plummeting prices of live
animals in Malaysia. The price of live pig is quoted at 38 baht (1.02 U.S.
dollars) per kilogram, compared with 48 baht (1.29 dollars) per kilogram in
markets in the southern provinces of Thailand.
The Livestock Department has informed governors in border provinces to keep
a close watch, for fear that price differences could entice animal and
carcass smuggling to Thailand.
It is reported that although aware of the disease, pork consumption in the
southern provinces does not appear to have fallen yet. Some 15,000 live
animals are delivered to market in the southern provinces every month.
Last week, Thai authorities banned the import of pork from Malaysia,
following a similar decision by Singapore.
[No mention made of the Hendra-like virus. - Mod.CHC
******
[2
PHILIPPINE RESPONSE
Date: Tue, 23 Mar 1999 20:24:05 -0500
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Xinhua News Agency; 23 Mar 1999 01:25

The Philippine government will impose a total ban on the import of pigs and
pork from Malaysia and its neighboring countries within the next 21 months.
National Meat Inspection Commission (NMIC) Executive Director Edgardo
Dimalanta said in an interview the ban will be made effective during the
period to protect the local livestock industry and consumers from
pig-related Japanese encephalitis (JE) viral disease.
Dimalanta said agriculture regional offices and quarantine officers of the
Bureau of Animal Industry will also closely monitor all ports to ensure
Malaysian pigs and pork could not enter the Philippines. These measures
will be undertaken by the government while Malaysia is addressing the
outbreak of the JE disease, including fogging and vaccination of people and
pigs, he said.
Dimalanta said Malaysian pigs and pork will be only allowed from coming
into the country once there is already an official declaration from
International Organization of Animal Diseases these are already safe for
consumption.
The official said the government has also to conduct a risk analysis of the
disease once Malaysia applies as exporter of pigs and pork in the country.
The Philippines so far has no importation of such products from Malaysia.
It now only ships in pigs and pork from Europe, Australia, Denmark, France,
Holland and Canada.
[Why 21 months and not, say, 20 or 22? Still no mention of the Hendra-like
virus. When this is all over, someone surely will have to estimate the
economic cost of this epizoodemic, including that cost component resulting
from delayed accurate diagnosis. - Mod.CHC
