[3
MALAYSIAN NEWSPAPER HIGLIGHTS - MARCH 23, 1999
Source: Asia Pulse; 22 Mar 1999 22:04

KUALA LUMPUR: An exercise to vaccinate 360,000 pigs in Negri Sembilan,
Selangor and Perak got under way today to curb the spread of the Japanese
encephalitis virus as authorities continued culling in the three major
outbreak areas of Bukit Pelanduk, Kampung Baru Sungai Nipah and Kampung
Sawah.
THE STAR - KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysia and Thailand will launch a joint border
patrol operation on Thursday to curb cross-border smuggling. Defence
Minister Abang Abu Bakar Abang Mustapa said today the operation would be
based at Pengkalan Hulu in Perak. ALOR STAR: Prime Minister Dr Mahathir
Mohamad today called on the people to be mindful of "Greeks bearing gifts",
saying that foreigners were still trying very hard to undermine the country.
[Personally, I'd be fascinated knowing to what this alludes. Sounds a bit
paranoid to me but I do not keep up with internal or external Malaysian
affairs. - Mod.CHC
KUALA LUMPUR: Health Minister Chua Jui Meng assures that burial of pigs at
designated places in JE-high risk areas will not result in pollution of
water resources as they are not water catchment areas. Nevertheless, pig
culling squads were told to exercise care when disposing pigs' carcasses to
minimise pollution. Meanwhile, Chua also says culling of pigs will be
expedited as more army and police personnel will be despatched to speed up
the work.
BERITA HARIAN - KUALA LUMPUR: Meanwhile, Chua Jui Meng also says the new
Hendra virus will not be easily infected. Consumers and housewives could
still handle pork in the normal way. So far there is no report indicates
that the new virus could be transmitted [to humans through close contact
with pork.
KUALA LUMPUR: As [of 6 p.m, March 21, nine more people from Negeri
Sembilan were admitted to hospitals for suspected JE disease. One of the
victims died [at admission. Meanwhile, another pig farmer from Bukit
Pelanduk died in the University Hospital yesterday, bringing the death toll
to 36.
KUALA LUMPUR: Another 7,625 pigs were killed on the third day of pig
culling exercise bringing the total number of animals killed to 13,038 so
far.
CYBERJAYA: It is not possible for the government to compensate pig farmers
for the pigs destroyed. Nevertheless, arrangement could be made for a
special lottery draw to help raise fund for them. Dr Mahathir says the
pressing task ahead is to curb the spread of the JE and destroy all
infected pigs.
KUALA LUMPUR: Health Minister Chua Jui Meng says work to vaccinate
residents from JE-high-risk areas was hampered because pig farmers, farm
workers and Muslims in the nearby vicinity were reluctant to have
themselves vaccinated. He urges people not to listen to rumours but go for
inoculation for their own safety.
KUALA LUMPUR: Dr Mahathir says the government's decision to allow special
lottery draw was not to compensate farmers, but merely to help them pull
through the current difficult time. He reiterates that it is impossible for
the government to compensate farmers for each and every pig killed.
KUALA LUMPUR: Other than Pulau Pinang which had unilaterally banned
movement of horses into the state, no other states imposed similar ruling.
Director of health and epidemic unit of the Veterinary Services Department
Dr Abdul Aziz says the department has no plan to conduct check on horses as
it is inadvisable to take hasty action before one knows more about the new
strain of virus.
[The Hendra-like virus is one newly discovered, therefore must be a newly
discovered strain. It is not a new strain of JE virus because it is not at
all related to JE virus. - Mod.CHC
