[5
Date: Thu, 25 Mar 1999 12:06:49 -0300
Source: media, Wed 24 Mar 1999

According to the health ministry, the death toll rose to 58 as of late
Tuesday, with another two deaths from a village in southwest Negeri
Sembilan. The virus first broke out in pig farms in the northern state of
Perak in October and was reported to have killed 15 people there before
spreading to Negeri Sembilan two months later.
Up to Sunday, 62,771 people had been vaccinated, 139,571 houses and 7,149
farms disinfected while 5,626 pig farms were inspected. More than 2,000
people have left their homes since the outbreak of JE, which is spread by
mosquitoes but harboured in pigs, began.
Health authorities said only 18 of deaths were so far confirmed to have
been caused by the JE virus, which causes inflammation of the brain.
Another encephalitis strain called "Hendra" -- discovered in 1994 when it
struck horses and humans in Brisbane, Australia -- has been found in some
patients. The Star newspaper said all 62 patients in hospitals nationwide
would be treated with the anti-viral ribavirin drug.
Eight members of the Atlanta-based Centers for Disease Control (CDC) and
two Australian experts have been called in to help curb the epidemic. So
far, CDC veterinary surgeon Tom Ksaizek and Australian animal health
laboratory project leader Hume Field have arrived.
Soldiers Wednesday continued the pig slaughter for a fifth day in three
villages in Negeri Sembilan. Around 327,000 animals are to be destroyed.
The culling operation resumed on Wednesday morning. Authorities had sent in
more troops on Tuesday and killed 6,770 pigs. This brought to 19,814 the
tally of pigs killed since the operation began on Saturday. Authorities had
planned to shoot about 35,000 pigs a day over 10 days.
The pig rearing industry, which earns 1.5 billion ringgit (US$395 million)
a year and employs some 300 000 people, has been crippled by the epidemic
as pork sales have slumped by nearly 70 percent.
[Still confusing JE virus and Hendra virus. My supicion is that this
confusion will be resolved within a short period of time, now that the
Australian and U.S. consultants have arrived to assist Ken lam and others
working on this epizoodemic problem. - Mod.CHC
